  "ascendancy_heading": "The Jewish covenant the New Testament writers worked in, the idiom that bent it, and the modern movement that made one reading required",
  "ascendancy": [
    "This is one of the deepest ironies in the project, and it deserves to be named clearly. The very tradition the New Testament writers were drawing on — the <strong>Jewish sacrificial system</strong> — is now claimed almost exclusively by the penal-substitution camp (\"Christ our Passover,\" \"the Lamb of God,\" \"without shedding of blood is no remission\"). But the Jewish sacrificial system, on its own terms, was not primarily a punishment-transfer. The Passover lamb was not punished in Israel's place; its blood <strong>marked the people of God for rescue</strong>, the way a sign on a doorpost marks a household for the angel of death to pass over. The Day of Atonement scapegoat was not punished either; it <strong>carried sin away</strong> into the wilderness, out of the camp, in a ritual of removal rather than of penalty. The whole apparatus was about purification, identification, covenant, and the wiping clean of what had defiled the community — not about an innocent victim absorbing a penalty owed by the guilty. When Jesus is called the Lamb of God, the New Testament writers are reaching for <em>that</em> Jewish vocabulary, not for a Roman courtroom.",
    "When the gospel moved into the medieval West, the frame quietly shifted. Anselm wrote <em>Cur Deus Homo</em> in the late eleventh century in a feudal world where every relationship was honor-shaped: sin became <em>dishonor</em> against the divine Lord, and the cross became the <em>satisfaction</em> owed for that dishonor. Five centuries later, the Reformers were working in a different idiom — the rise of legal and forensic categories in early-modern Europe, the courtroom and the contract — and Calvin recast satisfaction in those terms. The Lord became a Judge. The satisfaction became a <em>penalty</em>. The cross became a <em>sentence served</em>. Penal substitution proper had arrived, with a recognizable date and a recognizable cause: not a recovery of Scripture's original frame, but a translation of an older idea into the legal mind of a new age.",
    "For two and a half centuries after Calvin, penal substitution was <em>a</em> Protestant explanation of the cross among several. It became <em>the</em> explanation — the test of who was really saved — through the modern evangelical movement: nineteenth-century revivalism, the great preachers, the twentieth-century Crusades, the chain of bestselling tracts and gospel presentations that compressed the Christian message into a courtroom diagram you could share on a napkin. By the late twentieth century, in much of conservative Protestantism, to question penal substitution was to question the gospel itself — and that's the move, more than anything else in the doctrine's history, that the historical record actually can't support."
  ],
  "cards_heading": "Three passages where the translation and the tradition are doing more interpretive work than the original text asked of them",
