    {
      "ref": "Romans 3:25",
      "title": "The mercy seat, not the courtroom",
      "traditional": "<em>\"Whom God hath set forth to be a <strong>propitiation</strong> through faith in his blood…\"</em><br><br>Read as: <em>God's wrath toward sinners was rightly aroused, and the cross is the place where that wrath is turned aside by Christ's blood absorbing it.</em>",
      "charitable": "<em>\"Whom God set forth as the <strong>place where atonement is made</strong> — the mercy seat — through his blood, received by faith…\"</em><br><br>Read as: <em>the cross is the place where defilement is cleansed and the people of God are made whole — not where divine wrath is absorbed by an innocent victim.</em>",
      "lever": "The Greek word is <strong>hilastērion</strong>, and it is far more specific than English translations usually suggest. In the Greek Old Testament (the Septuagint, which Paul and the New Testament writers used constantly), <em>hilastērion</em> is the standard word for the <strong>mercy seat</strong> — the gold cover on the Ark of the Covenant in the Temple's Holy of Holies, the place where, on the Day of Atonement, the high priest sprinkled blood for the cleansing of the people's sins (Leviticus 16). When Paul calls Jesus a <em>hilastērion</em>, his Jewish readers heard a temple image: <strong>Jesus is the mercy seat — the place where atonement happens.</strong> Translating <em>hilastērion</em> as \"propitiation\" imports a Roman-legal idea (a sacrifice to <em>turn aside the anger</em> of an offended deity) that the Jewish image does not require. The mercy seat is not where wrath is absorbed by a substitute. It is where <strong>defilement is cleansed and the broken covenant is repaired.</strong>",
      "flag": "Wrath is genuinely a theme in Romans — Romans 1:18 opens with \"the wrath of God is revealed from heaven against all ungodliness\" — so the recovered reading isn't that God's wrath against evil is a myth. It's that the cross, as Paul describes it with the word <em>hilastērion</em>, is the <strong>mercy seat</strong> — the place where God deals with sin by <em>cleansing</em> it rather than by <em>punishing a substitute for it</em>. The traditional propitiation reading is grammatically possible; the recovered mercy-seat reading is what the Jewish word actually meant in the world Paul wrote in."
    },
    {
      "ref": "Isaiah 53:5–6",
      "title": "Wounded for our transgressions",
      "traditional": "<em>\"He was <strong>wounded for our transgressions</strong>, he was <strong>bruised for our iniquities</strong>: the chastisement of our peace was upon him; and with his stripes we are healed… the LORD hath <strong>laid on him the iniquity of us all</strong>.\"</em><br><br>Read as: <em>God transferred the punishment for our sins onto the suffering servant, and his suffering was the legal penalty being satisfied.</em>",
      "charitable": "<em>\"He was <strong>wounded because of our transgressions</strong>, he was <strong>crushed because of our iniquities</strong>: the chastisement that brings us peace was upon him; and by his bruises we are healed… the LORD has caused the iniquity of us all to <strong>meet in him</strong>.\"</em><br><br>Read as: <em>the servant suffers in solidarity with a sinful people whose sin caused his suffering — a servant whose pain heals because it carries the people's sin away, not because it satisfies a legal penalty.</em>",
      "lever": "Isaiah 53 is the single most important Old Testament passage in the penal-substitution case, and it does say something powerful about a suffering servant who bears the people's sin. What it says, and what later interpreters have read back into it, are not always the same thing. The Hebrew prepositions in verses 5–6 are ambiguous in a way the English usually flattens: <em>min</em> (translated \"for\") can mean <em>because of</em> (causal) or <em>on behalf of</em> (substitutionary), and the choice between them changes the theology. The Hebrew verb in verse 6 — <em>hipgia</em>, sometimes translated \"laid on\" — more literally means <em>caused to meet</em> or <em>interposed</em>, an image of convergence rather than legal transfer. Most importantly, the <strong>Jewish reading of this passage for two thousand years</strong> has not been that an innocent figure satisfies a legal penalty on behalf of the guilty; it has read the servant variously as Israel itself, as a remnant within Israel, or as a future figure whose suffering serves God's redemptive purposes — but not in the courtroom-and-penalty framework that Western Christianity later read into the text.",
      "flag": "Isaiah 53 is genuinely substitutionary in <em>some</em> sense — the servant's suffering is somehow connected to the people's sin and to their healing, and the New Testament repeatedly applies the chapter to Jesus' death (Acts 8, 1 Peter 2). The recovered reading isn't that there's no substitution in Isaiah 53; it's that the <em>specifically penal</em> framing — the suffering as legal penalty satisfying judicial wrath — is one possible interpretation of a chapter whose original language and original Jewish context point toward something subtler and more biblically rich."
    },
    {
      "ref": "Mark 10:45",
      "title": "Ransom, not penalty",
      "traditional": "<em>\"For even the Son of man came not to be ministered unto, but to minister, and to give his life <strong>a ransom for many</strong>.\"</em><br><br>Often read as: <em>Jesus paid the penalty our sins deserved, the \"ransom\" being a metaphor for the price of God's justice.</em>",
      "charitable": "<em>\"For even the Son of man came not to be served, but to serve, and to give his life <strong>a ransom for many</strong> — the price paid to free captives held against their will.\"</em><br><br>Read as: <em>the cross is a ransom paid to free people from bondage to sin and death — a rescue from captivity, not a legal penalty satisfying a judge.</em>",
      "lever": "The Greek word is <strong>lytron</strong>, and in the ancient world it had a specific and concrete meaning: the price paid to <em>free a captive</em> or <em>redeem a slave</em>. The classical and Jewish usage is consistent — <em>lytron</em> is what you pay to a kidnapper to get a hostage back, or what you pay at the temple to redeem a firstborn (Numbers 18:15–16). The cross-as-<em>lytron</em> image is therefore not a courtroom image but a <em>liberation</em> image: humanity is held in bondage to sin, death, and the powers, and Jesus' life is the price that buys our freedom. This is Christus Victor language dressed as ransom language, and it's what the early church ran with for a thousand years before Anselm moved the frame to honor and Calvin moved it to penalty.",
      "flag": "The ransom-language and the penal-language aren't necessarily incompatible — both involve something costly being given for the sake of someone else's freedom or forgiveness — and the New Testament uses both kinds of imagery without ranking them. The recovered reading isn't that ransom replaces all other atonement images. It's that <em>lytron</em> is the specific word the New Testament actually uses in this verse, and that word carries a captivity-and-liberation image, not a courtroom-and-penalty one. The plurality of metaphors in the New Testament is itself one of the strongest arguments against making any single metaphor required for salvation."
