  "moveon": [
    "If you find yourself wanting to push back here — wanting to say <em>\"but if Jesus didn't take the punishment we deserved, then what was the cross even for?\"</em> — sit with that for a minute, because I want to ask the question back rather than answer it.",
    "If the word Paul actually uses in Romans 3:25 is <em>hilastērion</em>, the <strong>mercy seat</strong>, and if the New Testament's Greek-speaking writers had a temple image in their heads rather than a courtroom — who decided that the courtroom would be the master metaphor for English-speaking Christians, and why does the mercy-seat reading have to fight for its place at the table when it's the one that matches the actual word? If the New Testament uses at least five distinct images for what the cross does — ransom, victory, reconciliation, recapitulation, sacrifice — who decided that <em>one</em> of those five would become the test of orthodoxy, and the other four would be optional decorations? If penal substitution in its sharp Reformation form is a thousand years old in a tradition that's two thousand years old — who decided that the <em>second half</em> of church history got to overwrite the <em>first half</em> on what the cross meant, and who profited by the overwriting?",
    "I'm not going to answer those questions for you. But notice that they're not asking whether penal substitution is true. They're asking who got to decide that <em>one</em> of the New Testament's many images would be promoted to the test of who is in the faith and who is out — and that question is harder to defend than the doctrine itself."
  ],
  "matters": "A great deal of how Christians describe God, holiness, justice, forgiveness, and even how parents discipline their children flows from the picture penal substitution paints: the assumption that wrongdoing must be matched by suffering, that justice and punishment are the same word, that love requires someone to be punished before it can be given. Whether you ever set foot in a church, that picture has shaped the moral imagination of the culture you live in — its prisons, its parenting, its politics, its appetite for retribution. The question of whether the cross <em>requires</em> that picture, or whether the Christian tradition holds older and larger ones, isn't just a church question. It's a question about what justice means.",
  "contested": [
    "The hardest texts for the recovered reading are real ones. Isaiah 53 speaks of one \"wounded for our transgressions,\" and any honest reader has to deal with the substitutionary weight of the chapter. Romans 3:25 uses <em>hilastērion</em>, and scholars genuinely disagree about whether the propitiation reading (wrath turned aside) or the expiation reading (sin cleansed) is closer to Paul's intent. 2 Corinthians 5:21 says God \"made him to be sin for us, who knew no sin,\" a verse penal substitution leans on hard. Substitution of <em>some</em> kind is genuinely in the Bible.",
    "The claim of this pillar is <strong>not</strong> that the cross isn't, in some way, \"for us\" or \"in our place\"; it's that the <em>specifically penal</em> framing — the cross as a <em>punishment</em> served on Jesus to satisfy a <em>legal</em> requirement — is one late reading among several true ones, born in feudal and legal categories, and not the only or original meaning of the cross. Anglicans, Catholics, Eastern Orthodox, Wesleyans, Mennonites, and many evangelicals hold the cross at the center of their faith without holding penal substitution as the required mechanism. They are not, by that fact, outside the gospel."
  ],
  "close": [
    "This is for the person who heard the gospel as: <em>you are guilty, God is angry, Jesus stepped between you and his Father's wrath</em> — and who, when they were honest with themselves, was never quite sure whether they were being loved or rescued from the one doing the loving.",
    "There's good news here, and it's bigger than the picture you were handed. The cross was, from the beginning, a deeper and wider thing than one transaction; it was a rescue from death and evil, a covenant marker like the blood on Israel's doorposts that identified you as one of God's, a reconciliation that undid the long estrangement, a recapitulation in which a new humanity was born in Christ, and — the early church sang this — the trampling-down of death by death.",
    "Whatever you keep of penal substitution, and you may keep it, well-loved, it is not the gate you have to pass through to be a Christian. The gate has always been Christ himself, and the picture of God you were taught to fear is not the only one the church has ever held. For most of its history, it wasn't even the main one."
  ]
